  "articleSummary": "This analytical article argues that adding engineers to a late software project inevitably delays it further due to quadratic communication overhead and mentorship costs, reinforcing Brooks' Law. It highlights how team scaling exponentially increases coordination paths (n(n-1)/2), drains existing staff's focus through interruptions, and requires a 3–6 month ramp-up period for new hires, while noting that modern tools like CI/CD pipelines and microservices only mitigate, rather than eliminate, these O(n²) constraints. Framed through mathematical formulas, the \"coordination tax,\" and Brooks' \"baby\" metaphor, the piece targets engineering managers, technical leads, and product stakeholders responsible for team sizing and project planning.",
